      <hedline>
        <hl1>A 5-Year-Old's Life: Work and Play</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Martin Lee letter comments on Oct 23 article on kindergartens that are introducing children to academic subjects; drawing</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''No Time for Napping in Today's Kindergarten'' (front page, Oct. 23):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''No Time for Napping in Today's Kindergarten'' (front page, Oct. 23):</p>
        <p>It is important for a child to be loved and valued for who he or she is and not just for academic performance. Educators should therefore beware that they do not place too many demands on young children; they may only be storing up trouble for the child in later life. Let children be children while they are able; there will be plenty of time for the pressures of academic study when they are older.</p>
        <p>MARTIN LEE  Indiana, Pa., Oct. 23, 2000</p>
      </block>
